CQC are currently going through a significant amount of change in the way we regulate health and social care organisations across England. Whilst we have always used information and intelligence to support our regulatory activities there is now an increased push to focus and drive these activities with better analysis and use of information. Our corporate strategy outlines the need for CQC to become a more efficient and effective regulator by improving how we:
•	Use information to identify when and what to inspect;
•	Use information and evidence to inform our inspection lines of enquiry and judgements;
•	Exploit qualitative information in our reporting;
•	Make information available to the public, providers and stakeholders

To support CQC the, the provision of legal services must therefore contain a mix of specialisms in commercial law in a public sector context with the following of particular note: -                                                 .
 •	re-procurement of business critical high value contracts of a complex nature; 
•	advice on multiple procurements and contracts that cover a breadth of different services with varying degrees of legal and commercial complexities;
•	re-procurement of existing contracts currently delivered via third sector providers through consortium agreements with other voluntary organisations and community groups;
•	TUPE implications and reviews;
•	review of Invitation to Tender (“ITT”), tender documentation, development of contract content that delivers CQC requirements and demonstrate value for money; 
•	advice on contracting with the third sector and relevant sector liabilities as voluntary bodies (dependent on legal status of entities) in public procurement and contract law;
•	flexibility on contract termination and variation on new remit areas as the model matures;
•	advice on intellectual property rights, data protection laws, freedom of information, confidentiality and in particular access to commercially sensitive information, together with the ability to provide advice on complex insolvency; 
•	advice and guidance on ITT and Contract models for volume based contracts to include financial management clauses and contract remedies  e.g. open book procedures and discounts;
•	review of ITT’s and contracts for robust management specifically on remedy management with a focus on key performance indicators; and the market and nature of the services  to be procured will require necessitate bespoke and complex conflict of interest clauses together with the appropriate advice and guidance in respect of their ongoing application.

1.	THE REQUIREMENT
To continue our journey to becoming a high performing organisation, CQC is looking to review and refresh its existing survey approach, content, and processes to ensure full alignment to our current organisational values, priorities and strategic direction.

Building on progress to date, the Contractor will work with us to help determine the best and most appropriate ways of harvesting employee opinion and feedback for us as an organisation, using innovative methods to measure engagement and drive follow up activity.

The Contractor should have a proven record of creative, effective and successful delivery of the requirements, ideally in a similar context. 
The supplier will work with CQC, advise and where appropriate, lead on the:
•	Review of our current approach and methodologies;
•	Review of current survey design and content;
•	Design of new survey content, including cognitive testing;
•	Management of survey processes including the set up and hosting of an online survey; 
•	Technical testing of survey;
•	Collection and management of survey data, response monitoring;
•	Technical support for staff during field period;
•	Provision of survey results in a number of formats (e.g. scorecards);
•	Statistical analysis, including an engagement index;
•	Possible qualitative design, delivery and analysis;
•	External benchmarking;
•	Reporting tool (client portal);
•	Equality and Diversity results report;
•	Presentation of results to CQC’s Executive Team;
•	Action planning process design;
•	Possible pulse check;
•	Possible flexible workforce survey (requirements of and for are to be confirmed).

The above is not an exhaustive list and other services may be required as part of the implementation of an employee survey.

Also additional services may be required as a result of, and informed by, a review of our existing approach (for example implementation of pulse surveys or a greater qualitative approach). 

CQC would like to see examples of your reporting templates and range of analyses.

This contract is for an initial one year in length however the Authority reserves the right to extend the contract by one further year subject to agreement by both parties.

SCOPE OF THE SERVICE

A Specialist Secure Patient Transport service is required for the transport of patients for Tees Esk & Wear Valleys NHS Foundation Trust. 

Secure Patient Transport for the purpose of this Agreement is defined as follows: 

'a service to transport patients that the Trust deem following a risk assessment requiring this level of transportation using the vehicle(s) 

Whilst anticipating that the majority of service requirements will be within the North East of England area the Contractor is expected to cover England, Scotland and Wales. 

The successful contractor must meet all Care Quality Commission (CQC) standards national standards and must be registered with the Care Quality Commission. 

The successful contractor must satisfy the Trust requirements in relation to Patient Confidentiality and Information Security.

The service must be available at any time of the day or night, including weekends, bank holidays and public holidays 24/7 365 days a year.

Vehicles 

All vehicles must be fit for purpose, comply with road traffic acts and local licensing authority and have appropriate insurance. 
The contractor must provide a variety of multi-purpose vehicles including covert vehicles with capacity to take up to 6 escorts with patients in a secure rear saloon and covert cell vehicles fitted with Home Office approved Cat B cell. 
Vehicle checks must be carried out by the driver prior to commencing any journey. 
The contractor must have resilient contingency plans to deal with breakdowns of vehicles.
Vehicles to include the following basic layout, as a minimum: 
• Driver isolated in cab area from rear saloon where up to 6 passengers may be located; 
• Intercom system or equivalent must be in place between the driver in the cab area and passengers; 
• Vehicles must be able to be contacted by your organisation; 
• Secure area within rear saloon for patient and escort must be seated; 
• Access to rear area to be via side loading door. Step access to support entry/exit if required. Grab rails at both sides of door to assist with access;
• Saloon to have heating system; 
• Vehicles to have wheelchair access and wheelchair anchoring suitable for manual and electronic wheelchairs when requested;
• Vehicles must have the ability to carry oxygen;
• Vehicles must have the capacity to transport patients belongings; 
• Vehicle must be equipped with first aid kits; 
• The supplier may be required to supply vehicles that have the ability to transfer bariatric patients in excess of 25 stone.

Initial term 24 months with an option for a further 2 x 12 months.

